== History ==
Originally named Shinmei Shrine, the site became Uozu Shrine in {{ill|1956|ja|昭和31st year|qq=draft|qq=draft}} following the integration of five shrines located in areas affected by the {{ill|Uozu Great Fire|ja|魚津大火|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. The new shrine building was completed on {{ill|June 1, 1965|ja|昭和40th year 6月1日|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref>『北日本新聞』1965th year 5月21日付朝刊12面（富山新川版）『来月1日から遷座祭 魚津神社が完成』より。</ref><ref name="tzin" /><ref name="p330">『富山県神社誌』（1983rd year 11月10日、富山県神社庁発行）346頁。</ref> 

In {{ill|1965|ja|昭和40th year|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the Atago Shrine, formerly located on the grounds of Uozu Municipal Ōmachi Elementary School, was relocated to the north of the main shrine. In {{ill|1968|ja|昭和43rd year|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, a large torii gate (8.5 meters tall) was erected through a donation.<ref>『富山新聞』1968th year 9月18日付朝刊10面『魚津神社に大鳥居』より。</ref> In {{ill|1970|ja|昭和45th year|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, a sumo ring was added to the grounds.<ref>『北日本新聞』1970th year 8月1日付朝刊（富山新川版）12面『魚津相撲場が完成』より。</ref>

== Shrine and Grounds ==
* Construction began: September 30, 1963 (groundbreaking ceremony held on September 24)<ref>『北日本新聞』1963rd year 9月20日付朝刊7面『二千三百万円で新築 7th year ぶりに解決の魚津神社』より。</ref>
* Completed: May 30, 1965
* Architect: Matsumoto Taisaku
* Builder: Asano Nobuharu
* Shrine grounds: 1,238 tsubo<ref name="tzin" />

== Integrated Shrines ==
[[File:Atago-sha (Uozu)009.jpg|thumb|Atago Shrine]]
* Shinmei Shrine (Shinmei-chō) – Established on March 17, 702 (Daibō 2)<ref name="tzin" />.
* Hi-no-Miya Shrine (Shimomuragi-chō) – Rebuilt during the Genki era<ref name="tzin" />.
* Inari Shrine (Kanayachō) – Built during the Bunsei era<ref name="tzin" />.
* Ichihime Shrine (Shinkanayachō) – Relics moved to Uozu Shrine in 1979.
* Kizuki Shrine (Kōnoura-chō) – Established during the Bunsei era by the Uozu magistrate.<ref name="tzin" />

== Annual Events ==
* January 26 – {{ill|Atago Fire Festival|ja|愛宕社の火祭り|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
* June 4–6 – Uozu Shrine Festival
** Locally known as "Shinmeihan's Festival," this event attracts numerous stalls along the central streets of Uozu.
** Historical children’s kabuki floats were once paraded, using traditional techniques and lacquerware craftsmanship. Some relics are preserved in the {{ill|Uozu History and Folklore Museum|ja|魚津歴史民俗博物館|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

